the other one is going to go down.

104
00:05:08.610 --> 00:05:12.745
And a good example would be the tradeoff
between short-term nonfinancial and

105
00:05:12.745 --> 00:05:14.740
short-term financial.

106
00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:18.130
Again, under accounting rules,
if you spend money on research and

107
00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:20.650
development, right,
that could be a nonfinancial.

108
00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:23.058
Are we doing the research
projects we want?

109
00:05:23.058 --> 00:05:26.340
In the short-run,
all the money you spent on research and

110
00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:30.200
development, makes your short-run
accounting profits go down.

111
00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.470
That's how the accounting rules work.

112
00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:35.598
Now in the long-run, obviously,
if you think these are good research and

113
00:05:35.598 --> 00:05:39.088
development projects, ultimately you're
going to get better financial results.

114
00:05:39.088 --> 00:05:43.150
But in the short-run there's a tradeoff,
so what we need to decide is, okay when is

115
00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:46.255
this going to pay off and what kind
of tradeoff am I willing to make?

116
00:05:46.255 --> 00:05:50.301
And finally, again, probably one of
the hardest things to do with nonfinancial

117
00:05:50.301 --> 00:05:53.630
measures, what performance
targets do we want?

118
00:05:53.630 --> 00:05:57.400
More is not necessarily better with these.

119
00:05:57.400 --> 00:05:59.770
So the steps we're going to
have to go through again is,

120
00:05:59.770 --> 00:06:00.680
what should we be measuring?

121
00:06:01.722 --> 00:06:04.400
How we're going to weight these very,
very different performance measures

122
00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:07.780
when I'm trying to analyze
the potential financial results?

123
00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:11.080
How do I make tradeoffs between
short-term and long-term?

124
00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:13.320
And finally, how am I going to
set these performance targets?

125
00:06:15.950 --> 00:06:17.830
Now there's lots of ways we
could go about doing this,

126
00:06:17.830 --> 00:06:21.440
and it's not like companies
don't make these decisions.

127
00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:23.570
We make these decisions all the time.

128
00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:25.305
Now I could do it just based on intuition.

129
00:06:25.305 --> 00:06:28.860
I've been in this business a long time,
I know this industry,

130
00:06:28.860 --> 00:06:30.260
I know our customer base.

131
00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:32.150
It must be true.

132
00:06:32.150 --> 00:06:34.894
That if x goes up,
ys going to happen in the long-run.

133
00:06:35.950 --> 00:06:40.059
Well, that may be right, but we live in
a very dynamic world that maybe that was

134
00:06:40.059 --> 00:06:42.504
right last year and
it's not right this year.

135
00:06:42.504 --> 00:06:46.319
Or maybe your intuition is 90% correct.

136
00:06:46.319 --> 00:06:49.265
It's that 10% that may not be correct,
that's really going to give you

137
00:06:49.265 --> 00:06:52.210
competitive advantage and
we want to understand that.

138
00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:55.380
Now I could go beyond that,
get past one person's intuition and

139
00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:57.440
use management consensus.

140
00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:59.750
We get a whole bunch of really smart
people to sit around the room and

141
00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:04.270
decide these nonfinancial measures are
going to lead to these financial results.

142
00:07:04.270 --> 00:07:07.980
Except most of us have been in
meetings where consensus really means

143
00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:09.130
who's loudest.

144
00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:12.540
Okay, whoever's loudest and
talks the most, they win.

145
00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:15.290
Consensus does not really
mean it's necessarily right.

146
00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:18.220
Now obviously it's a good place to start,
right?

147
00:07:18.220 --> 00:07:22.090
We could use one of these measurement
frameworks or benchmarking studies.

148
00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:23.400
Use the balance scorecard,

149
00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:26.430
you've got four categories, I have to
have measures in each one of those.

150
00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:29.550
That must be true that they
lead to financial performance.

151
00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:31.014
I could use a benchmarking study.

152
00:07:31.014 --> 00:07:35.114
I go out, I hire a consultant,
I ask them, what is best practices?

153
00:07:35.114 --> 00:07:38.810
Let me tell you, this is the worst
question I ever get as a consultant.

154
00:07:38.810 --> 00:07:41.398
Best practices means you're doing
exactly what the other guy is doing.

155
00:07:41.398 --> 00:07:45.101
No, what you want to do is,
how can I figure out in my company,

156
00:07:45.101 --> 00:07:48.761
what nonfinancial measures I
need to make my strategy work?

157
00:07:48.761 --> 00:07:52.120
Not what are other guys using
to make their strategy work.

158
00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:53.930
We could do informal data analyses.

159
00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:56.110
We kind of plot some stuff
on Excel spreadsheet, and

160
00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:58.235
they kind of look like they're
correlated with each other,

161
00:07:58.235 --> 00:08:00.390
that kind of looks like when this goes up,
that one goes up as well.

162
00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:04.450
What we're going to talk about
today is not, let's get past that.

163
00:08:04.450 --> 00:08:07.970
Okay, let's try do to more rigorous
predictive analytics methods, right.

164
00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:12.360
The tools are there, most of our
software packages have the capability.

165
00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:16.870
As companies say, we have lots of data,
but we have little information.

166
00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:21.770
What we're trying to do is, turn
the data that almost every company has,

167
00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:24.650
into information or
something that I can say,

168
00:08:24.650 --> 00:08:28.210
when this measure goes up,
what's going to happen on the other side?

169
00:08:28.210 --> 00:08:30.170
Data is not the problem in companies.

170
00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:32.220
Coming up with measures is not a problem.

171
00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:34.180
The problem is coming up with data or

172
00:08:34.180 --> 00:08:38.700
measures that tell me something
about future financial performance.

173
00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:41.930
Now there is a theory we can start
use to structure this analysis, and

174
00:08:41.930 --> 00:08:43.990
it's a good way to think about this.

175
00:08:43.990 --> 00:08:48.880
The first thing we have to start out
is developing something called a causal

176
00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:51.790
business model or
a strategy map, that describes

177
00:08:51.790 --> 00:08:55.200
what are the value drivers in your company
and how are they linked to strategy?

178
00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:57.120
So here's what you want to think about.

179
00:08:57.120 --> 00:09:00.440
What a causal model is,
is an if then statement.

180
00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:03.800
If this happens,
then I expect something else to happen.

181
00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:06.720
Now what you want to do is
start out with your strategy.

182
00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:10.099
Pull out your strategic plan, and
for those of you who have never seen

183
00:09:10.099 --> 00:09:13.440
a strategic plan,
they are actually extremely high level.

184
00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:16.511
going to move into this market,
we're going to go into this product line,

185
00:09:16.511 --> 00:09:17.510
we're going to divest.

186
00:09:17.510 --> 00:09:20.000
They actually don't tell you
how you're going to get there.

187
00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.908
What a causal model is,
is start out with a strategy and say,

188
00:09:23.908 --> 00:09:28.600
these are the steps I need to take,
from a to z to make this strategy work.

189
00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:30.710
First, I've got to do that.

190
00:09:30.710 --> 00:09:32.668
Now when I do that,
that should lead to this next thing.

191
00:09:32.668 --> 00:09:34.620
Which should lead to the next thing?

192
00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:39.430
There's a cause and effect relationship
between putting the strategy in, and

193
00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:42.230
getting the ultimate financial results.

194
00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:45.540
So what you want to do is,
start out with this causal model.

195
00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:47.980
Here's a strategy,
here are the steps I need to take.

196
00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:51.080
Once you know those steps,

197
00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:55.140
then you can lay out what are called
the value propositions or hypotheses.

198
00:09:55.140 --> 00:10:00.060
How is it that we as an organization,
think we're going to create value?

199
00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:03.740
Now value, in many for-profit
companies' going to be financial.

200
00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:06.660
If you're a nonprofit, it doesn't have to
be financials, just here's the ultimate

201
00:10:06.660 --> 00:10:11.120
goals I want to get, if you think
about it a strategy is a hypothesis.

202
00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:13.690
Here is how I think I will get there.

203
00:10:13.690 --> 00:10:16.300
The question is, when you implement
the strategy, will it work?

204
00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:18.710
Well that's testing the hypothesis, right?

205
00:10:18.710 --> 00:10:23.390
I've got these steps I need to go through,
I'm predicting that a happens,

206
00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:26.030
then b then c,
well let's see if that's true.

207
00:10:26.030 --> 00:10:29.100
When I implement a let's come
up with a performance measure.

208
00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:30.000
Does it predict b?

209
00:10:31.100 --> 00:10:33.760
If b happens, does it predict c?

210
00:10:33.760 --> 00:10:37.430
Because what you don't want to do is wait
to see if financial results work or not.

211
00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:41.220
Am I taking the intermediate
steps that I need to do,

212
00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:45.310
to achieve my financial goals that
ultimately lead to financial performance?

213
00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:47.900
Because financial performance
could be a long way out there.

214
00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:50.290
I don't want to wait to
see if this works or not.

215
00:10:50.290 --> 00:10:53.170
Okay, now that you have that,
here are the steps I need.

216
00:10:53.170 --> 00:10:56.670
I'm going to come up with performance
measures to see if I've done the steps.

217
00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:58.040
Let's test those hypothesis.

218
00:10:59.050 --> 00:11:00.920
If your causal model again says,

219
00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:05.560
I need to do a, that's going to lead to b,
that's going to lead to c, let's test it.

220
00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:09.700
When I implement a,
let's come up with a measure that says,

221
00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:11.320
did I implement it well?

222
00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:14.500
Then let's see if there's a relationship
when that measure related to

223
00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:15.420
a goes up and down.

224
00:11:16.480 --> 00:11:18.450
Did the measure related to b go up and
down?

225
00:11:18.450 --> 00:11:22.761
Right, that's the hypothesis
that if I do a, b will change.

